message.content:
You are a senior React Native test engineer reviewing a PR. The PR configures ts-jest to enable TypeScript type-checking during Jest test runs, and fixes 2 test files that broke due to the migration.

PROBLEM:
When ts-jest compiles TypeScript, `import React from 'react'` becomes `const react_1 = require('react')`. Jest hoists `jest.mock()` calls above imports. If a mock factory contains JSX (which compiles to `react_1.default.createElement()`), it fails because `react_1` is not yet defined when the mock factory runs.

FIX APPLIED TO AirlineMilesMarketplace.test.tsx:
```tsx
// Before
jest.mock('react-native-webview', () => {
  const { View } = require('react-native');
  return {
    WebView: (props: any) => <View testID="webview" {...props} />,
  };
});

// After
jest.mock('react-native-webview', () => {
  const React = require('react');
  const { View } = require('react-native');
  return {
    WebView: (props: any) => React.createElement(View, { testID: 'webview', ...props }),
  };
});
```

FIX APPLIED TO MyOrdersRewardProgram.test.tsx:
```tsx
// Before
jest.mock('react-native', () => {
  const RN = jest.requireActual('react-native');
  return {
    ...RN,
    FlatList: props => {
      const { data = [], renderItem, ListEmptyComponent, testID } = props;
      if (!data || data.length === 0) {
        return (
          <RN.View testID={testID}>
            {ListEmptyComponent && <ListEmptyComponent />}
          </RN.View>
        );
      }
      return (
        <RN.View testID={testID}>
          {data.map((item, index) => {
            props.keyExtractor?.(item, index);
            return renderItem({ item, index });
          })}
        </RN.View>
      );
    },
  };
});

// After
jest.mock('react-native', () => {
  const React = require('react');
  const RN = jest.requireActual('react-native');
  return {
    ...RN,
    FlatList: (props: any) => {
      const { data = [], renderItem, ListEmptyComponent, testID } = props;
      if (!data || data.length === 0) {
        return React.createElement(
          RN.View,
          { testID },
          ListEmptyComponent && React.createElement(ListEmptyComponent, null),
        );
      }
      return React.createElement(
        RN.View,
        { testID },
        data.map((item: any, index: number) => {
          props.keyExtractor?.(item, index);
          return renderItem({ item, index });
        }),
      );
    },
  };
});
```

RESULTS: All 113 tests pass across 17 suites.

Review criteria:
1. Is the fix correct and complete?
2. Are there any behavioral differences between the before/after versions?
3. Are the explicit type annotations (props: any, item: any, index: number) appropriate?
4. Could there be other test files with the same JSX-in-mock-factory pattern that weren't caught?
5. Is the React.createElement pattern the right approach, or is there a better alternative?

Respond with APPROVED, CHANGES_REQUESTED, or COMMENT.

